Big Mobility Data Analytics for Public Health Data/Code Interview Task¶

Submitted by: Saketh Reddy Regatte

The goal of this exercise is to link two longitudinal spatial datasets ( NYC taxi trips & NYC restaurant locations), to perform some descriptive analyses and visualizations, and to describe how to set up a predictive model.

Data Preparation¶

Assumptions:

  1. We will focus on analyzing the locations of restaurants (specified by the combination of their building, street, and zipcode features) and not their inspection results.

  2. All taxi trip destinations during lunchtime (11:30am - 2pm) and dinnertime (5pm - 9pm) were to restaurants.

Based on the above listed assumptions let us filter out the dataframes and extract the quality data required for this analysis.

In [20]:
# Creating the pointers for lunchtime and dinnertime
start_time1 = pd.to_datetime('11:30:00').time()
end_time1 = pd.to_datetime('14:00:00').time()
start_time2 = pd.to_datetime('17:00:00').time()
end_time2 = pd.to_datetime('21:00:00').time()
# Filter out the necessary records where taxi trips are for restaurants based on tpep_dropoff_datetime. 
taxi_df = taxi_df.set_index('tpep_dropoff_datetime').between_time(start_time1, end_time1).\
          append(taxi_df.set_index('tpep_dropoff_datetime').between_time(start_time2, end_time2)).\
          reset_index()

2. Link the two datasets spatially¶

Finding restaurants that were (assumed to be) visited at the destination of a taxi ride during lunchtime or dinnertime. Implement this by finding the closest match to a restaurant address within a 50m buffer (radius of 50m) around a latitude longitude point in the taxi data; that is, count matches only if they are within 50m of the taxi destination.

To link dataframes spatially we will convert the pandas dataframes to Geopandas Dataframes and will apply .sjoin() on the dataframes

But the Restaurants dataframe is missing latitude and longitudes column. Les first retrieve the latitudes and longitudes.

In [ ]:
'''
Python script to retrive latitude and longitude of the location given the address.
The script will request Nominatim API for location details, then latitudes and longitudes are retreived.
The script take long time to run as it comprises of multiple API calls.
Hence the coordinates are retrived once and stored as a csv file for frequent access. 
'''
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
from shapely.geometry import Point
from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim

taxi_df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/data.csv")
restaurant_df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/DOHMH_New_York_City_Restaurant_Inspection_Results.csv")

restaurant_df["LOCATION"] = restaurant_df["BUILDING"] + ", "+ restaurant_df["STREET"]+ ", " + restaurant_df["BORO"]

geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent='my_app',country_bias = "United States")
# Define a function to geocode an address and return its latitude and longitude
def geocode_address(address):
    try:
        location = geolocator.geocode(address)
        return (location.latitude, location.longitude)
    except:
        return None
address_list = list(restaurant_df["LOCATION"])
coordinates_list=[]
c = 0
for i in address_list:
  if c%100 == 0:
    print(c)
  c+=1
  try:
    location = geolocator.geocode(i)
    coordinates_list.append((location.latitude, location.longitude))
  except:
    coordinates_list.append(None)
print(len(coordinates_list))

coordinates_list = [("x", "x") if v is None else v for v in coordinates_list]
print(len(coordinates_list))

restaurant_coordinates_df = pd.DataFrame(coordinates_list, columns = ["LATITUDE","LONGITUDE"])
restaurant_coordinates_df.to_csv("COORDINATES_DF.csv", index = False)

# create Point geometry objects from (lon,lat)
restaurant_geom = [Point(xy) for xy in zip(restaurant_df.LONGITUDE, restaurant_df.LATITUDE)]
# set initial coordinate ref system, and geometry column to the dataframe
restaurants_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(restaurant_df, geometry=restaurant_geom,crs="EPSG:4326")
restaurants_gdf_utm33N = restaurants_gdf.to_crs(epsg=32633)

'''
Create the buffer aroud the restaurant location. 
If the taxi dropoff coordinates end within this buffer we can assume that is a 
restaurant trip.
'''
restaurants_gdf_utm33N['buffer_geometry'] = restaurants_gdf_utm33N.geometry.buffer(50)
restaurants_gdf_utm33N = restaurants_gdf_utm33N.rename(columns={'geometry':'original_geometry', 'buffer_geometry':'geometry'})\
                                               .set_geometry('geometry')

'''
Preparing linked_data to perform the exploratory analysis using Keplergl 
'''
# Considering TimeofTheDay feature from taxi_df and Restaurant Counts from restaurant_df
g = linked_df.groupby(['RESTAURANT'])
i = g.size()
j = g[["LATITUDE","LONGITUDE","TimeOfTheDay"]].first()
pop_restaurants = pd.concat([i, j], 1).reset_index()
pop_restaurants = pop_restaurants.rename(columns={0:'Counts'})
pop_restaurants = pop_restaurants.sort_values(by='Counts', ascending=False).reset_index()

'''
Grouping te linked data and finding the mean of the trip_distance to find the 
average distance travelled by people to get the Cuisine_type specified by CUISINE_DESCRIPTION
'''
cuisine_trip = linked_data_1.groupby('CUISINE_DESCRIPTION').mean('trip_distance').reset_index()
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
cuisine_trip = cuisine_trip.sort_values(by='trip_distance', ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize= (20,10))
sns.swarmplot(data=cuisine_trip, y='trip_distance', x='CUISINE_DESCRIPTION')
plt.xlabel('Cuisine Types')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
# set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Travel Distance')
# set the title
plt.title('Swarm Plot of Cuisine Types and Travel Distance')
# show the plot
plt.show()

4a How far do people travel based on different types of cuisine (“CUISINE DESCRIPTION”)?

  • From the above Swarm plot it is evident that in order to get CUISINE named "CREOLE/CAJUN", trip_distance is more. That means, people need to travel more distance to get it. On the other hand, Californian foods are more easily available.

5. Describe how you would set up a predictive model¶

Decision Trees are selected for this analysis Feature Set will include:

  • Trip distance (miles)
  • Borough of restaurant
  • Time of day
  • Number of passengers in the taxi
  • Day of the week

MODEL BUILDING PROCESS

  1. Data Preparation: Combined the taxi and restaurant datasets spatially based on the assumption that all taxi trips during lunchtime and dinnertime were to restaurants. Preprocessed and cleaned the data, including encoding categorical variables (e.g. Borough, Day of Week, Time of Day).

  2. Feature Selection: selected the relevant features that can help in predicting the cuisine type of a restaurant. In this case, we can use Trip Distance, Borough of Restaurant, Time of Day, Number of Passengers, and Day of the Week.

  3. Splitting the Data: Data needed to be split into training and testing sets.

  4. Model Selection: Choose a decision tree model for the classification problem. There are various algorithms available, such as ID3, C4.5, CART, etc. Choose an appropriate algorithm based on the size and complexity of the dataset.

  5. Model Training: Train the decision tree model on the training set. Tune hyperparameters such as maximum depth, minimum samples per leaf, etc. to avoid overfitting.

  6. Model Evaluation: Evaluate the model's performance on the testing set using metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score.

  7. Model Optimization: If the model's performance is not satisfactory, perform feature engineering and hyperparameter tuning to optimize the model.

  8. Predictions: Once the model is trained and optimized, use it to make predictions on new data.

  9. Monitoring and Maintenance: Monitor the model's performance over time and maintain it by retraining on new data or updating hyperparameters as needed.

Additional data sources that can be used to improve the predictive model are:

  • Yelp API: Additional information such as restaurant ratings, reviews, and menu items can be obtained from Yelp's API to enhance the feature set.
  • Weather Data: Weather conditions may affect people's food choices and can be a useful feature to include in the model.
  • Demographic Data: Demographic data such as age, income, and ethnicity of the restaurant's surrounding population may influence cuisine preferences and can be added to the feature set.
  • Traffic data: Traffic data can be used to understand the impact of traffic on restaurant patronage. For example, if there is a lot of traffic in a certain area, people may be less likely to visit restaurants in that area.
  • Events data: Events data can be used to understand the impact of events on restaurant patronage. For example, if there is a concert or sports game happening in a certain area, people may be more likely to visit restaurants in that area before or after the event.
